You are in control of your own life. No one holds a gun to your head and demands that you play Everquest. There is no pusher standing next to you, telling you &quot;Just one more hit, you will feel better, I promise you&quot;.<br>
<br>
You bought the game of your own free will. You subscribed to the game at your own free will. Everquest was placed (Alphabetically in most places) among a vast number of other computer software titles. So its not like anyone forced it upon you to pick that game up and take it home. Nope. You did all that on your own.<br>
<br>
From Kaif:<br>
You are in control of your own life. No one holds a gun to your head and demands that you smoke.  There is no pusher standing next to you, telling you &quot;Just one more hit, you will feel better, I promise you.&quot;<br>
<br>
You bought the cigarettes of your own free will.  You went to the convenience store at your own Free Will.  Your brand of choice was placed (Alphabetically in most places) among a vast number of other cigarette brands.  So it's not like anyone forced it upon you to pick up that cigarette and smoke it.  Nope.  You did all that on your own.<br>
<br>
Same arguement stands, cigarette companies (admittedly evil) are getting ravaged by law suits.<br>
<br>
I don't think the case has any merit.  However, just because something is legal and you don't *have* to buy it doesn't mean it isn't harmful.  And if you are the maker of the item in question, you better have your ducks in a row, because the second someone burns themselves on a hot iron and feels like it, the jackals will come running.<br>
<br>
Kaif<br>
